# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: task-queues
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] Kafka was originally developed at LinkedIn, and was subsequently open sourced in early 2011.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] Jay Kreps, Neha Narkhede and Jun Rao helped co-create Kafka.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] Graduation from the Apache Incubator occurred on 23 October 2012.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] Jay Kreps chose to name the software after the author Franz Kafka because it is "a system optimized for writing", and he liked Kafka's work.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] Apache Kafka is a distributed log-based messaging system that guarantees ordering within individual partitions rather than across the entire topic.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] Unlike queue-based systems, Kafka retains messages in a durable, append-only log, allowing multiple consumers to read at different offsets.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] Kafka uses manual offset management, giving consumers control over retries and failure handling.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] If a consumer fails to process a message, it can delay committing the offset, preventing further progress in that partition while other partitions remain unaffected.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] This partition-based design enables fault isolation and parallel processing while allowing ordering to be maintained within partitions, depending on consumer handling.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] In 2025, Apache Kafka introduced "Queues for Kafka", adding share groups as an alternative to consumer groups.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] This feature enables queue-like semantics where consumers can cooperatively process records from the same partitions, with individual message acknowledgment and delivery tracking.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] Unlike traditional consumer groups where partitions are exclusively assigned, share groups allow the number of consumers to exceed partition count, making it ideal for work-queue patterns while maintaining Kafka's durability and scalability benefits.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] This development addresses the common challenge of "over-partitioning" that many Kafka users face.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] Kafka Connect (or Connect API) is a framework to import/export data from/to other systems.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] It was added in the Kafka 0.9.0.0 release and uses the Producer and Consumer API internally.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] The Connect framework itself executes so-called "connectors" that implement the actual logic to read/write data from other systems.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] Kafka Streams (or Streams API) is a stream-processing library written in Java.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] It was added in the Kafka 0.10.0.0 release.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] The library allows for the development of stateful stream-processing applications that are scalable, elastic, and fully fault-tolerant.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] The main API is a stream-processing domain-specific language (DSL) that offers high-level operators like filter, map, grouping, windowing, aggregation, joins, and the notion of tables.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] Additionally, the Processor API can be used to implement custom operators for a more low-level development approach.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] The DSL and Processor API can be mixed, too.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] For stateful stream processing, Kafka Streams uses RocksDB to maintain local operator state.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] Because RocksDB can write to disk, the maintained state can be larger than available main memory.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] For fault-tolerance, all updates to local state stores are also written into a topic in the Kafka cluster.
[src:task-queues/apache-kafka] This allows recreating state by reading those topics and feed all data into RocksDB.
[src:task-queues/celery-software] The execution units, called *tasks*, are executed concurrently on one or more worker nodes using multiprocessing, eventlet or gevent.
[src:task-queues/celery-software] Tasks can execute asynchronously (in the background) or synchronously (wait until ready).
[src:task-queues/celery-software] Celery is used in production systems, for services such as Instagram, to process millions of tasks every day.
[src:task-queues/celery-software] Celery is written in Python, but the protocol can be implemented in any language.
[src:task-queues/celery-software] It can also operate with other languages using webhooks.
[src:task-queues/celery-software] There is also a Ruby-Client called RCelery, a PHP client, a Go client, a Rust client, and a Node.js client.
[src:task-queues/celery-software] Celery requires a message broker to run.
[src:task-queues/celery-software] As of October 2024, Redis and RabbitMQ are supported and actively maintained and monitored.
[src:task-queues/celery-software] Amazon SQS is supported and maintained but does not support worker inspection and management at runtime, while Zookeeper and Kafka are currently in experimental development.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] In computer science, **message queues** and **mailboxes** are software-engineering components typically used for inter-process communication (IPC), or for inter-thread communication within the same process.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] They use a queue for messaging – the passing of control or of content.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Group communication systems provide similar kinds of functionality.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] The message queue paradigm is a sibling of the publisher/subscriber pattern, and is typically one part of a larger message-oriented middleware system.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Most messaging systems support both the publisher/subscriber and message queue models in their API, e.g.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Competing Consumers pattern enables multiple concurrent consumers to process messages on the same message queue.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Message queues implement an asynchronous communication pattern between two or more processes/threads whereby the sending and receiving party do not need to interact with the message queue at the same time.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Messages placed onto the queue are stored until the recipient retrieves them.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Message queues have implicit or explicit limits on the size of data that may be transmitted in a single message and the number of messages that may remain outstanding on the queue.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Many implementations of message queues function internally within an operating system or within an application.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Such queues exist for the purposes of that system only.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Other implementations allow the passing of messages between different computer systems, potentially connecting multiple applications and multiple operating systems.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] These message queuing systems typically provide resilience functionality to ensure that messages do not get "lost" in the event of a system failure.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Examples of commercial implementations of this kind of message queuing software (also known as message-oriented middleware) include IBM MQ (formerly MQ Series) and Oracle Advanced Queuing (AQ).
[src:task-queues/message-queue] There is a Java standard called Java Message Service, which has several proprietary and free software implementations.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Real-time operating systems (RTOSes) such as VxWorks and QNX encourage the use of message queuing as the primary inter-process or inter-thread communication mechanism.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] This can result in integration between message passing and CPU scheduling.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Early examples of commercial RTOSes that encouraged a message-queue basis to inter-thread communication also include VRTX and pSOS+, both of which date to the early 1980s.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] The Erlang programming language uses *processes* to provide concurrency; these processes communicate asynchronously using message queuing.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] The message queue software can be either proprietary, open source or a mix of both.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] It is then run either on premise in private servers or on external cloud servers (message queuing service).
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Examples on hardware-based messaging middleware vendors are Solace, Apigee, and IBM MQ.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] In a typical message-queueing implementation, a system administrator installs and configures message-queueing software (a queue manager or broker), and defines a named message queue.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Or they register with a message queuing service.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] An application then registers a software routine that "listens" for messages placed onto the queue.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Second and subsequent applications may connect to the queue and transfer a message onto it.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] The queue-manager software stores the messages until a receiving application connects and then calls the registered software routine.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] The receiving application then processes the message in an appropriate manner.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] These are all considerations that can have substantial effects on transaction semantics, system reliability, and system efficiency.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Historically, message queuing has used proprietary, closed protocols, restricting the ability for different operating systems or programming languages to interact in a heterogeneous set of environments.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] An early attempt to make message queuing more ubiquitous was Sun Microsystems' JMS specification, which provided a Java-only abstraction of a client API.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] This allowed Java developers to switch between providers of message queuing in a fashion similar to that of developers using SQL databases.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] In practice, given the diversity of message queuing techniques and scenarios, this wasn't always as practical as it could be.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] These protocols are at different stages of standardization and adoption.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] The first two operate at the same level as HTTP, MQTT at the level of TCP/IP.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Some proprietary implementations also use HTTP to provide message queuing by some implementations, such as Amazon's SQS.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] This is because it is always possible to layer asynchronous behaviour (which is what is required for message queuing) over a synchronous protocol using request-response semantics.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] However, such implementations are constrained by the underlying protocol in this case and may not be able to offer the full fidelity or set of options required in message passing above.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Many of the more widely known communications protocols in use operate synchronously.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] The HTTP protocol – used in the World Wide Web and in web services – offers an obvious example where a user sends a request for a web page and then waits for a reply.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] However, scenarios exist in which synchronous behaviour is not appropriate.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] For example, AJAX (Asynchronous JavaScript and XML) can be used to asynchronously send text, JSON or XML messages to update part of a web page with more relevant information.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Google uses this approach for their Google Suggest, a search feature which sends the user's partially typed queries to Google's servers and returns a list of possible full queries the user might be interested in the process of typing.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] This list is asynchronously updated as the user types.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Other asynchronous examples exist in event notification systems and publish/subscribe systems.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] In both of the above examples it would not make sense for the sender of the information to have to wait if, for example, one of the recipients had crashed.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Applications need not be exclusively synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] In all these sorts of situations, having a subsystem which performs message-queuing (or alternatively, a broadcast messaging system) can help improve the behavior of the overall system.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] There are two common message queue implementations in UNIX.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] One is part of the SYS V API, the other one is part of POSIX.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] UNIX SYS V implements message passing by keeping an array of linked lists as message queues.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Each message queue is identified by its index in the array, and has a unique descriptor.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] A given index can have multiple possible descriptors.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] UNIX gives standard functions to access the message passing feature.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] This system call takes a key as an argument and returns a descriptor of the queue with the matching key if it exists.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] flag is set, it makes a new message queue with the given key and returns its descriptor.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Used to receive a message from a given queue descriptor.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] The caller process must have read permissions for the queue.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Used to change message queue parameters like the owner.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] A message queue can be deleted only by its creator, owner, or the superuser.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] The POSIX.1-2001 message queue API is the later of the two UNIX message queue APIs.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] It is distinct from the SYS V API, but provides similar function.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] The unix man page `mq_overview(7)` provides an overview of POSIX message queues.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] Graphical user interfaces (GUIs) employ a message queue, also called an *event queue* or *input queue*, to pass graphical input actions, such as mouse clicks, keyboard events, or other user inputs, to the application program.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] The windowing system places messages indicating user or other events, such as timer ticks or messages sent by other threads, into the message queue.
[src:task-queues/message-queue] The GUI application removes these events one at a time by calling a routine called `getNextEvent()` or similar in an event loop, and then calling the appropriate application routine to process that event.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] In computing, the **producer-consumer problem** (also known as the **bounded-buffer problem**) is a family of problems described by Edsger W.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] Dijkstra wrote about the unbounded buffer case: "We consider two processes, which are called the 'producer' and the 'consumer' respectively.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The producer is a cyclic process and each time it goes through its cycle it produces a certain portion of information, that has to be processed by the consumer.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The consumer is also a cyclic process and each time it goes through its cycle, it can process the next portion of information, as has been produced by the producer ...
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] He wrote about the bounded buffer case: "We have studied a producer and a consumer coupled via a buffer with unbounded capacity ...
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] And about the multiple producer-consumer case: "We consider a number of producer/consumer pairs, where pairi is coupled via an information stream containing ni portions.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] Per Brinch Hansen and Niklaus Wirth saw soon the problem of semaphores: "I have come to the same conclusion with regard to semaphores, namely that they are not suitable for higher level languages.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The original semaphore bounded buffer solution was written in ALGOL style.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The buffer can store N portions or elements.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The "number of queueing portions" semaphore counts the filled locations in the buffer, the "number of empty positions" semaphore counts the empty locations in the buffer and the semaphore "buffer manipulation" works as mutex for the buffer put and get operations.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] If the buffer is full, that is the number of empty positions is zero, the producer thread will wait in the P(number of empty positions) operation.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] If the buffer is empty, that is the number of queueing portions is zero, the consumer thread will wait in the P(number of queueing portions) operation.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The V() operations release the semaphores.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] As a side effect, a thread can move from the wait queue to the ready queue.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The P() operation decreases the semaphore value down to zero.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The V() operation increases the semaphore value.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] As of C++ 20, semaphores are part of the language.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] Dijkstra's solution can easily be written in modern C++.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The variable buffer_manipulation is a mutex.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The semaphore feature of acquiring in one thread and releasing in another thread is not needed.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The lock_guard() statement instead of a lock() and unlock() pair is C++ RAII.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The lock_guard destructor ensures lock release in case of an exception.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] This solution can handle multiple consumer threads and/or multiple producer threads.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] Per Brinch Hansen defined the monitor: I will use the term monitor to denote a shared variable and the set of meaningful operations on it.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The purpose of a monitor is to control the scheduling of resources among individual processes according to a certain policy.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] Tony Hoare laid a theoretical foundation for the monitor.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The monitor is an object that contains variables `buffer`, `head`, `tail` and `count` to realize a circular buffer, the condition variables `nonempty` and `nonfull` for synchronization and the methods `append` and `remove` to access the bounded buffer.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The monitor operation wait corresponds to the semaphore operation P or acquire, signal corresponds to V or release.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The circled operation (+) are taken modulo N.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The presented Pascal style pseudo code shows a Hoare monitor.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] A Mesa monitor uses `while count` instead of `if count`.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The C++ version needs an additional mutex for technical reasons.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] It uses assert to enforce the preconditions for the buffer add and remove operations.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The very first producer-consumer solution in the Electrologica computers used 'channels'.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] Hoare defined channels: An alternative to explicit naming of source and destination would be to name a port through which communication is to take place.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The port names would be local to the processes, and the manner in which pairs of ports are to be connected by channels could be declared in the head of a parallel command.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] Brinch Hansen implemented channels in the programming languages Joyce and Super Pascal.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The Plan 9 operating system programming language Alef, the Inferno operating system programming language Limbo have channels.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The program entry point is at function `threadmain`.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The function call `ch = chancreate(sizeof(ulong), 1)` creates the channel, the function call `sendul(ch, i)` sends a value into the channel and the function call `p = recvul(ch)` receives a value from the channel.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The programming language Go has channels, too.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The Go producer-consumer solution uses the main Go routine for consumer and creates a new, unnamed Go routine for the producer.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The two Go routines are connected with channel ch.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] This channel can queue up to three int values.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The statement `ch := make(chan int, 3)` creates the channel, the statement `ch <- produceMessage()` sends a value into the channel and the statement `recvMsg := range ch` receives a value from the channel.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The allocation of memory resources, the allocation of processing resources, and the synchronization of resources are done by the programming language automatically.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] Leslie Lamport documented a bounded buffer producer-consumer solution for one producer and one consumer: We assume that the buffer can hold at most b messages, b >= 1.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] In our solution, we let k be a constant greater than b, and let s and r be integer variables assuming values between 0 and k-1.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] We assume that initially s=r and the buffer is empty.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] By choosing k to be a multiple of b, the buffer can be implemented as an array B [0: b - 1].
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The producer simply puts each new message into B[s mod b], and the consumer takes each message from B[r mod b].
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The algorithm is shown below, generalized for infinite k.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The Lamport solution uses busy waiting in the thread instead of waiting in the scheduler.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] This solution neglects the impact of scheduler thread switch at inconvenient times.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] If the first thread has read a variable value from memory, the scheduler switches to the second thread that changes the variable value, and the scheduler switches back to the first thread then the first thread uses the old value of the variable, not the current value.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] Atomic read-modify-write solves this problem.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] Modern C++ offers `atomic` variables and operations for multi-thread programming.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The following busy waiting C++11 solution for one producer and one consumer uses atomic read-modify-write operations `fetch_add` and `fetch_sub` on the atomic variable `count`.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The circular buffer index variables `head` and `tail` are thread-local and therefore not relevant for memory consistency.
[src:task-queues/producer-consumer-problem] The variable `count` controls the busy waiting of the producer and consumer thread.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] In software architecture, the **publish–subscribe pattern** (**pub/sub**) is a messaging pattern in which message senders, called **publishers**, categorize messages into classes (or *topics*), and send them without needing to know which components will receive them.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] Message recipients, called **subscribers**, express interest in one or more classes and only receive messages in those classes, without needing to know the identity of the publishers.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern decouples the components that produce messages from those that consume them, and supports asynchronous, many-to-many communication.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] The publish–subscribe model is commonly contrasted with message queue-based and point-to-point messaging models, where producers send messages directly to consumers.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publish–subscribe is a sibling of the message queue paradigm, and is typically a component of larger message-oriented middleware systems.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many modern messaging frameworks and protocols, such as the Java Message Service (JMS), Apache Kafka, and MQTT, support both the pub/sub and queue-based models.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern provides greater network scalability and supports more dynamic topologies, but can make it harder to modify the publisher’s logic or the structure of the published data.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] Compared to synchronous patterns like RPC and point-to-point messaging, publish–subscribe provides the highest level of decoupling among architectural components.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, it can also lead to semantic or format coupling between publishers and subscribers, which may cause systems to become entangled or brittle over time.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] In publish–subscribe systems, subscribers typically receive only a subset of messages.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] In most pub/sub systems, publishers and subscribers communicate through a central intermediary such as a message broker or event bus.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] The broker receives messages from publishers and forwards them to the appropriate subscribers, optionally performing store and forward, priority queuing, or other routing logic.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] Some pub/sub systems use **brokerless** architectures, in which publishers and subscribers discover each other and exchange messages directly.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, the Data Distribution Service (DDS) middleware uses IP multicast and metadata sharing to establish communication paths.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokerless systems require construction of overlay networks, often using Small-World topologies to enable efficient routing.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] It was shown by Jon Kleinberg that efficient decentralized routing requires Navigable Small-World topologies, which are employed in federated or peer-to-peer pub/sub systems.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] Locality-aware pub/sub networks use low-latency links to reduce message propagation time.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] One of the earliest publicly described pub/sub systems was the "news" subsystem of the Isis Toolkit, presented at the 1987 ACM Symposium on Operating Systems Principles (SOSP '87).
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] As distributed systems became more common, the publish–subscribe model evolved to emphasize asynchronous messaging and broker-mediated communication, setting it apart from the more tightly coupled observer pattern.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publishers are loosely coupled to subscribers, and need not even know of their existence.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] With the topic being the focus, publishers and subscribers are allowed to remain ignorant of system topology.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] Each can continue to operate as per normal independently of the other.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] In the traditional tightly coupled client–server paradigm, the client cannot post messages to the server while the server process is not running, nor can the server receive messages unless the client is running.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many pub/sub systems decouple not only the locations of the publishers and subscribers but also decouple them temporally.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] A common strategy used by middleware analysts with such pub/sub systems is to take down a publisher to allow the subscriber to work through the backlog (a form of bandwidth throttling).
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] Pub/sub provides the opportunity for better scalability than traditional client-server, through parallel operation, message caching, tree-based or network-based routing, etc.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] Outside of the enterprise environment, on the other hand, the pub/sub paradigm has proven its scalability to volumes far beyond those of a single data center, providing Internet-wide distributed messaging through web syndication protocols such as RSS and Atom.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] These syndication protocols accept higher latency and lack of delivery guarantees in exchange for the ability for even a low-end web server to syndicate messages to (potentially) millions of separate subscriber nodes.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] Redundant subscribers in a pub/sub system can help assure message delivery with minimal additional complexity.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, a factory may utilize a pub/sub system where equipment can publish problems or failures to a subscriber that displays and logs those problems.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] If the logger fails (crashes), equipment problem publishers won't necessarily receive notice of the logger failure, and error messages will not be displayed or recorded by any equipment on the pub/sub system.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a client/server system, when an error logger fails, the system will receive an indication of the error logger (server) failure.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, the client/server system will have to deal with that failure by having redundant logging servers online, or by dynamically spawning fallback logging servers.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] This adds complexity to the client and server designs, as well as to the client/server architecture as a whole.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a pub/sub system, redundant logging subscribers that are exact duplicates of the existing logger can be added to the system to increase logging reliability without any impact to any other equipment on the system.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] The feature of assured error message logging can also be added incrementally, subsequent to implementing the basic functionality of equipment problem message logging.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] The most serious problems with pub/sub systems are a side-effect of their main advantage: the decoupling of publisher from subscriber.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] A pub/sub system must be designed carefully to be able to provide stronger system properties that a particular application might require, such as assured delivery.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] The pub/sub pattern scales well for small networks with a small number of publisher and subscriber nodes and low message volume.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, as the number of nodes and messages grows, the likelihood of instabilities increases, limiting the maximum scalability of a pub/sub network.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] For pub/sub systems that use brokers (servers), the argument for a broker to send messages to a subscriber is in-band, and can be subject to security problems.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers might be fooled into sending notifications to the wrong client, amplifying denial of service requests against the client.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers themselves could be overloaded as they allocate resources to track created subscriptions.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] Even with systems that do not rely on brokers, a subscriber might be able to receive data that it is not authorized to receive.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] An unauthorized publisher may be able to introduce incorrect or damaging messages into the pub/sub system.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] This is especially true with systems that broadcast or multicast their messages.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] Transport Layer Security (SSL/TLS)) can prevent unauthorized access, but cannot prevent damaging messages from being introduced by authorized publishers.
[src:task-queues/publish-subscribe-pattern] Architectures other than pub/sub, such as client/server systems, are also vulnerable to authorized message senders that behave maliciously.
[src:task-queues/rabbitmq] Written in Erlang, the RabbitMQ server is built on the Open Telecom Platform framework for clustering and failover.
[src:task-queues/rabbitmq] Client libraries to interface with the broker are available for all major programming languages.
[src:task-queues/rabbitmq] The source code is released under the Mozilla Public License.
[src:task-queues/rabbitmq] Originally developed by Rabbit Technologies Ltd. which started as a joint venture between LShift and CohesiveFT in 2007, RabbitMQ was acquired in April 2010 by SpringSource, a division of VMware.
[src:task-queues/rabbitmq] The project became part of Pivotal Software in May 2013, which then got acquired back by VMware in December 2019.
[src:task-queues/rabbitmq] This section gives sample programs written in Python (using the *pika* package) for sending and receiving messages using a queue.
[src:task-queues/rabbitmq] The following code fragment establishes a connection, makes sure the recipient queue exists, then sends a message and finally closes the connection.
